      <h2 style="font-weight:700;font-family:Open Sans;color:#01498B;margin:3px 0 0 0;">Chris Forney</h2>
      <h3 style="font-weight:300;text-transform:uppercase;font-family:'museo-sans';color:#008FB4;margin:3px 0 15px 0;">Principal</h3>
      <div class="profile" style="color:#676767;font-size:16px;letter-spacing:0.5px;"><p>A highly experienced project leader with advanced subject-matter expertise in sustainable design and construction, Chris Forney serves Brightworks clients throughout the country while managing the firm’s offices in Southern California and New York. He also serves on the firm’s management committee.</p>
<p>Chris trained at the University of Oregon School of Architecture, ranked first in the United States for sustainable design by the journal <em>DesignIntelligence</em>. Before joining Brightworks, Chris was a designer for architecture firms in Boston and Portland, where he led his firms’ sustainability programs.</p>
<p>During this time, Chris was Brightworks’ client on the design and construction of large-scale, high-rise condominium towers in downtown Los Angeles, recognized as the first and second LEED certified condominiums ever developed in California. Since then, Chris has become one of the country&#8217;s foremost experts in sustainable design for multifamily housing.</p>
<p>Today, Chris offers clients expertise in:</p>
<ul>
<li>LEED v4</li>
<li>Living Building Challenge</li>
<li>Federal Guiding Principles for High Performance and Sustainable Buildings</li>
<li>CalGreen</li>
<li>Federal Highway Administration Infrastructure Voluntary Evaluation Sustainability Tool (INVEST)</li>
<li>LEED for New Construction (LEED NC)</li>
<li>LEED for Core &amp; Shell (LEED CS)</li>
<li>LEED for Commercial Interiors (LEED CI)</li>
<li>North American Sustainable Transportation Council STARS</li>
<li>The Natural Step</li>
<li>Carbon Disclosure Project</li>
<li>Federal Executive Order 13514</li>
</ul>
<p>For his leadership in sustainable design, Chris has been an elected member of the Cascadia Green Building Council, the largest chapter of the U. S. Green Building Council and originators of the Living Building Challenge. Prior to joining Cascadia’s board, Chris served on the executive committee of the organization’s Portland chapter.</p>
<p>In addition to his service to CascadiaGBC, Chris was a founding member of the North American Sustainable Transportation Council, which created the Sustainable Transportation Analysis &amp; Rating System (STARS).</p>
